                <h3 class="text-center">Getting Started</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Explore your state’s homeschool laws.</li>
                    <li>Talk to other homeschool mothers.</li>
                    <li>
                        Explore homeschool methods – you don’t have to choose just one, or even any, just learn
                        ways to approach homeschooling. Then you can find your families sweet spot. This often
                        takes a few years to perfect, some experimentation, and adjustments.
                    </li>
                    <li>Look at curriculum options.</li>
                    <li>
                        Join Facebook homeschool groups and see what others are doing and recommending.
                        This adds ideas to your toolbox.
                    </li>
                    <li>If you feel you want support, explore the co-ops and part-time school options.</li>
                    <li>Consider how you will keep a record of what you do.</li>
                    <li>
                        If you really what to do this and are not sure where to start, sign up for a coaching
                        session. You can do it just once to get your confidence up and get pointed in the right
                        direction, or more than once to figure out how to jump in.
                    </li>
                </ul>
